04574nam a22005535i 9780226000947DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132013ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013014690  a9780226000947  a(DE-B1597)524574  a(OCoLC)862050286  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBQ974.A3588bB73 2013 4aBQ974.A3588bB73 2013 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a294.3/910922231 aBraun, Erik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Birth of Insight :bMeditation, Modern Buddhism, and the Burmese Monk Ledi Sayadaw /cErik Braun. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b6 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBuddhism and Modernity00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tOn Transliteration and Abbreviation -- tIntroduction: Ledi Sayadaw and the Gifts of the Buddha -- t1. The Best of Times and the Worst: Ledi Sayadaw’s Formative Period -- t2. The Great War of the Commentaries: Ledi Sayadaw’s Abhidhamma Controversy -- t3. “In the Hands of All the People”: Ledi Empowers the Laity -- t4. “In This Very Life”: Lay Study of the Abhidhamma -- t5. The Birth of Insight -- tConclusion: The Death of Ledi and the Life of Insight -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInsight meditation, which claims to offer practitioners a chance to escape all suffering by perceiving the true nature of reality, is one of the most popular forms of meditation today. The Theravada Buddhist cultures of South and Southeast Asia often see it as the Buddha’s most important gift to humanity. In the first book to examine how this practice came to play such a dominant—and relatively recent—role in Buddhism, Erik Braun takes readers to Burma, revealing that Burmese Buddhists in the colonial period were pioneers in making insight meditation indispensable to modern Buddhism. Braun focuses on the Burmese monk Ledi Sayadaw, a pivotal architect of modern insight meditation, and explores Ledi’s popularization of the study of crucial Buddhist philosophical texts in the early twentieth century. By promoting the study of such abstruse texts, Braun shows, Ledi was able to standardize and simplify meditation methods and make them widely accessible—in part to protect Buddhism in Burma after the British takeover in 1885. Braun also addresses the question of what really constitutes the “modern” in colonial and postcolonial forms of Buddhism, arguing that the emergence of this type of meditation was caused by precolonial factors in Burmese culture as well as the disruptive forces of the colonial era. Offering a readable narrative of the life and legacy of one of modern Buddhism’s most important figures, The Birth of Insight provides an original account of the development of mass meditation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDharma (Buddhism) 0aDharma (Buddhism). 0aMeditationxBuddhism. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  ameditation, buddhism, self knowledge, peace, burma, monk, ledi sayadaw, truth, theravada buddhist, insight, suffering, southeast asia, colonial period, colonialism, race, conquest, invasion, religion, social control, government, spirituality, dharma, abhidhamma controversy, laity, nonfiction, philosophy, eastern, mindfulness, spiritual growth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226000947423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226000947/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGr